Introduction

Objective: Predicting survival of Titanic passengers To do this, I will explroe the data and perform pre-processing techniques to make the data set suitable for the model fitting that follows.

A quick graph analysis of suitable attributes to the response target variable (Survived) is also performed to also identify key variables that impact the probability of survival rate through inspection.

Implementation of classication models using each of the following techniques are also used to determine the feature importance within the dataset. - Decision Tree - Bagging - Boosting - Random Forest

colSums(is.na(train))
## PassengerId    Survived      Pclass        Name         Sex         Age 
##           0           0           0           0           0         177 
##       SibSp       Parch      Ticket        Fare       Cabin    Embarked 
##           0           0           0           0           0           0
colSums(train=="")
## PassengerId    Survived      Pclass        Name         Sex         Age 
##           0           0           0           0           0          NA 
##       SibSp       Parch      Ticket        Fare       Cabin    Embarked 
##           0           0           0           0         687           2

From looking at the dataset, we can see that there are a lot of NA values within the variable “Age”. Thus, we would first need to clean and tidy up the data before proceeding.

I have decided to replace the NA values with the mean of their corresponding group of “Pclass” attribute. This was decided due to the fact that it seemed more of a “closer” susbstitute then simply imputing the values with either mean or median.

for (i in which(sapply(train, is.numeric))) {
  for (j in which(is.na(train[, i]))) {
    train[j, i] <- mean(train[train[, "Pclass"] == train[j, "Pclass"], i],  na.rm = TRUE)
  }
}

# Test class also seem to have some NA values
for (i in which(sapply(test, is.numeric))) {
  for (j in which(is.na(test[, i]))) {
    test[j, i] <- mean(test[test[, "Pclass"] == test[j, "Pclass"], i],  na.rm = TRUE)
  }
}

In terms of the cells that consist of empty strings, it would be unreasonable to replace 687 values in the attribute “Cabin” as the data only contains 891 rows.

However, for the “Embarked” attribute I have decided to replace the values with to the most occurring value, “S”.

table(train$Embarked)
## 
##       C   Q   S 
##   2 168  77 644
train$Embarked[train$Embarked==""]="S"
train$Embarked = as.factor(train$Embarked)
train$Embarked = droplevels(train$Embarked)
attach(train)

Graph Analysis

Investigating the relationship of attributes towards survival

ggplot(data=train, aes(x=Pclass, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_bar(stat="count", position="fill") +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Pclass Survival Rate")

From the graph above, 1st class passengers seem to have on average a higher survival rate than 3rd class passengers.

ggplot(data=train, aes(x=Sex, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_bar(stat="count", position="fill") +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Sex Survival Rate")

From the graph above, female on average had a higher survival rate than males.

ggplot(data=train, aes(x=Age, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(position="fill") +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Age Survival Rate")

From the graph above, younger and older people had a higher survival rate.

ggplot(data=train, aes(x=SibSp, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_bar() +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("SibSp Survival Rate")

From the graph above, passengers that had fewer siblings/spouses on average had a higher survival rate.

ggplot(data=train, aes(x=Parch, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_bar() +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Parch Survival Rate")

From the graph aobve, passengers that had fewer parents/children on average had a higher survival rate.

# Since SibSp and Parch were similar in content, we could further analyse them by combining them together to estimate the "Family" size each passenger travelled with. 
train$FamSize = as.integer(train$SibSp + train$Parch + 1)
ggplot(data=train, aes(x=FamSize, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_bar(stat="count", position="fill") +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Survival Rate in terms of family size")

From the graph above, passengers that had a smaller family size on average had a higher survival rate.

ggplot(data=train, aes(x=Fare, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(position="fill") +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Fare Survival Rate")

This attribute can be considred to be similar to Pclass attribute, however this one is not too conclusive to be able to draw any conclusions from.

train$cabinID = substr(train$Cabin, 1, 1)
ggplot(train, aes(x=cabinID, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(stat="count", position="fill") +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Cabin Survival Rate")

Even though there was not too many cabin data that was gathered, it is still interesting to see that those in cabin B, D & E had a higher survival rate than A, G or T.

ggplot(data=train, aes(x=Embarked, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_bar(position="fill") +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Port of Embarkation Survival Rate")

This is also something interesting to look at, but boarding your transport at a certain time would not determine any survival rate in any way.

ggplot(train, aes(x=Embarked, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(stat="count", position="fill")+
  facet_wrap(~Pclass) +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Survival Rate in terms of Embarked and Pclass")

By creating the graph above, it also further proves that first class passengers havea higher survival rate on average more so than third class passengers.

ggplot(train, aes(x=FamSize, fill=Survived)) +
  geom_histogram(stat="count", position="fill")+
  facet_wrap(~Pclass) +
  ylab("Frequency") + ggtitle("Survival Rate in terms of Family size and Pclass")

The graph above also further adds to the point between survival rate and family size. Where on average, travelling with a family is safest in first or second class in comparison to travelling on third class.

Classification Models

Creation of the models to predict survival rate

# Only keep the numerical variables that are more significant
#(Pclass, Sex, Age, SibSp, Parch, Fare, Embarked, Title, Survived)
train_comp = train[,c(3,5,6,7,8,10,12,15,2)]

# Decision Tree *****
titanic.tree = tree(Survived ~., data = train_comp)

# Bagging *****
titanic.bag = bagging(Survived ~., data = train_comp, mfinal = 5)

# Boosting  *****
titanic.boost = boosting(Survived ~., data = train_comp, mfinal = 5)

# Random Forest  *****
titanic.rf = randomForest(Survived ~., data = train_comp, ntree=100)

## Overall Feature Importance 
rf.importance = as.table(c(titanic.rf$importance[c(3),],0,0,titanic.rf$importance[c(5,1,2,4),],0))
class.var = cbind(titanic.bag$importance, titanic.boost$importance, rf.importance)
class.var = cbind(class.var, rowSums(class.var)) # Sums the row and combines to the dataframe
colnames(class.var) = c("Bagging", "Boosting", "Random Forest", "Total")
class.var = as.data.frame(class.var)
class.var = class.var[order(-class.var$Total),] # sort by descending order (Total)

Predicting Survival Rate using these Models

Creation of csv files to compare and measure the accuracy of the models

# Predicting survival rate using decision tree model
tpredict = predict(titanic.tree, test, type = "class")
t.res = data.frame(test$PassengerId, tpredict)
names(t.res) = c("PassengerID", "Survived")
write.csv(t.res, file="tree.csv", row.names=FALSE)
# Predicting survival rate using baggging model
bpredict = predict.bagging(titanic.bag, newdata = test)
bag.res = data.frame(test$PassengerId, bpredict$class)
names(bag.res) = c("PassengerID", "Survived")
write.csv(bag.res, file="bag.csv", row.names=FALSE)
# Predicting survival rate using boosting model
bopredict = predict.boosting(titanic.boost, newdata = test)
boost.res = data.frame(test$PassengerId, bopredict$class)
names(boost.res) = c("PassengerID", "Survived")
write.csv(boost.res, file="boost.csv", row.names=FALSE)
# Predicting survival rate using random forest model
rfpredict = predict(titanic.rf, test)
rf.res = data.frame(test$PassengerId, rfpredict)
names(rf.res) = c("PassengerID", "Survived")
write.csv(rf.res, file="rf.csv", row.names=FALSE)

Conclusion

The best classifcation model out of all, resulted in the Random Forest with a score of 0.78468.
